Here is a full ‚Äúdeveloper mode‚Äù plan plus the exact files you need, fully compatible with your current **phuntroo** project and GitHub Pages, with:

* Avatar gallery (multiple real human avatars)
* Easy way to add new AI-generated human-face avatars from the internet
* Simple ‚Äúdownload from URL‚Äù helper (browser-only)
* No servers, no GPUs, no paid APIs

We will keep everything **inside `web/public/avatar`** so it does not break your existing React/Vite frontend.

---

## 0. High-level architecture

We will add:

1. `web/public/avatar/index.html`

   * Standalone avatar viewer + gallery (Three.js via CDN, no build step needed)
   * Reads avatar metadata from `avatars.json`
   * Shows 3D avatar, webcam view, basic motion

2. `web/public/avatar/avatars.json`

   * List of all available avatars (file path + thumbnail + name + tags)

3. `web/public/avatar/avatars/`

   * All `.glb` avatar files (human body / human faces)
   * Thumbnail `.jpg` or `.png` images used by gallery

You will:

* Add new AI-generated avatars by dropping `.glb` + thumbnail into `avatars/`
* Add one JSON entry in `avatars.json`
  No other code changes needed.

---

## 1. Create folders in your repo

In GitHub (or locally), make sure this structure exists:

```text
phuntroo/
  web/
    public/
      avatar/
        index.html          ‚Üê we will create/replace this
        avatars.json        ‚Üê we will create this
        avatars/
          (all .glb + thumbnails go here)
```

If `avatar` or `avatars` folder does not exist, create them.

---

## 2. Create `avatars.json`

Create a new file:

`phuntroo/web/public/avatar/avatars.json`

Paste this content (you can adjust names and files as you add more avatars):

```json
[
  {
    "id": "default_indian",
    "name": "Default Indian Avatar",
    "file": "avatars/avatar.glb",
    "thumb": "avatars/avatar.jpg",
    "source": "ReadyPlayerMe",
    "notes": "Full body Indian-style realistic avatar."
  },
  {
    "id": "ai_face_1",
    "name": "AI Human Face 1",
    "file": "avatars/ai_face_1.glb",
    "thumb": "avatars/ai_face_1.jpg",
    "source": "Artbreeder + Meshcapade",
    "notes": "Realistic young adult female face."
  },
  {
    "id": "ai_face_2",
    "name": "AI Human Face 2",
    "file": "avatars/ai_face_2.glb",
    "thumb": "avatars/ai_face_2.jpg",
    "source": "PlaygroundAI + Meshcapade",
    "notes": "Realistic male face avatar."
  },
  {
    "id": "business_woman",
    "name": "Business Woman",
    "file": "avatars/business_woman.glb",
    "thumb": "avatars/business_woman.jpg",
    "source": "ReadyPlayerMe",
    "notes": "Realistic professional outfit avatar."
  }
]
```

Important:

* `file` is **relative to `/avatar/`**, so `"avatars/xxx.glb"` is correct.
* `thumb` is the URL to the thumbnail image (jpg/png) in the same `avatars/` folder.
* You can add more objects to this array when you add new avatars.

---

## 3. Put your `.glb` + thumbnails into `avatars/`

Inside:

`phuntroo/web/public/avatar/avatars/`

Upload:

* `avatar.glb` + `avatar.jpg` (your main body avatar, maybe Indian female)
* `ai_face_1.glb` + `ai_face_1.jpg` (AI face ‚Üí converted to 3D)
* `ai_face_2.glb` + `ai_face_2.jpg`
* `business_woman.glb` + `business_woman.jpg`

You can get these from:

* ReadyPlayerMe (.glb full body)
* AI-image ‚Üí Meshcapade / VanceAI 3D ‚Üí .glb
* FBX ‚Üí `fbxtogl.com` ‚Üí .glb

As long as you put the files in this folder and reference them correctly in `avatars.json`, they will show up.

---

